<h4 id="drive-guide---bald-mountain-from-cowpen-mountain">Drive Guide - Bald Mountain from Cowpen Mountain</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Right/straight/south out of parking (NOT left/east)  on USFS-64 and go 4.1</li>
  <li>Straight through ‚ÄúConasauga T‚Äù (NOT left) onto USFS-67 and go 3.5</li>
  <li>Park at the driveway to the group camping area (on left); trailhead is across the road</li>
</ul>

<h4 id="drive-guide---bald-mountain-to-atlanta">Drive Guide - Bald Mountain TO Atlanta</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Head east on FS-68, toward the ‚ÄúConasauga T‚Äù and go 3.5</li>
  <li>R at ‚ÄúConasauga T‚Äù to stay on FS-68 (straight becomes FS-64) and go 3.2</li>
  <li>Sharp L on FS-90 (becomes Wilderness Trail) and go 1.5</li>
  <li>L on Gates Chapel Rd and go 5.4</li>
  <li>L on GA-52 and follow GA-52 for 6 miles.</li>
  <li>R onto bridge and go 0.1</li>
  <li>R on GA-515/GA-575</li>
</ul>

<h4 id="trail-guide">Trail Guide</h4>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Duration</strong>: 0:30 up, 0:15 down; 0.5 miles</li>
  <li><strong>Navigation</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Follow the trail 0.5 miles. Starts northeast, then east, then northeast again.</li>
      <li>The trail is basically straight up the mountain, with no descent.  It goes up, but it is probably the easiest of the Georgia 10-pointers, given the modest slope and short distance.  The actual summit is off the trail about 75‚Äô and is covered with evergreens, but the trail passes through the activation zone.</li>
      <li>In summer, the trail and the summit are overgrown with greenery.  Bluejeans are advised, due to thorns crowing the trail.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Trailhead altitude</strong>: 3621‚Äô @ Trailhead @ 34.86117, -84.63482</li>
  <li><strong>Summit altitude</strong>: 4005‚Äô</li>
  <li><strong>GPS tracks/waypoints</strong>:
    <ul>
      <li>Trailhead: 34.86117, -84.63482</li>
      <li>Summit: 34.86450, -84.62830</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 id="summit-guide">Summit Guide</h4>

<ul>
  <li>Hang antenna from tree: Yes.</li>
  <li>Space to guy mast: Challenging in spring/summer, due to underbrush.</li>
  <li>Cell coverage: Verizon SMS, AT&amp;T SMS (intermittent), and APRS ‚Äì all worked.</li>
  <li>Note that there are flush toilets at the picnic area at Lake Conasauga.  You have to pay $2 to park there, and don‚Äôt forget that the picnic area isn‚Äôt open for the full March-December season that the road is open.</li>
</ul>

